This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing and topic modeling. It could also belong to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as topic modeling is often used in information retrieval tasks. Additionally, the paper proposes a new assumption for topic modeling, which could be of interest to researchers in the fields of machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG and cs.AI). Finally, the paper's focus on improving the performance of topic models could also make it relevant to the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
